In the experiments on the small LC 4% dataset (38 processed features) and the Taiwan Credit Default dataset (82 processed features), the computation of the group quality metric $  Q  $ for the Owen-Domain, Owen-Data, and Owen-Model methods occasionally returned NaN values. This occurred when the agglomerative clustering step in build_data_groups and build_model_groups resulted in a single cluster, making the between-group correlation term undefined. To resolve this and maintain conceptual consistency with the definition of $  Q  $, the compute_Q function was extended with a robust fallback: when only one group is present (or no cross-group comparisons are possible), $  Q  $ is set to 1.0, representing perfect grouping quality. Following this correction, all 36 Owen-related rows in LC4_result.csv and TW_result.csv now contain valid numeric $  Q  $ values, and the corresponding Q vs I scatter plots display all 12 data points per Owen variant, consistent with the complete results obtained on the larger LC 10% dataset.
